<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="1" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="#fff5ba" WIDTH="150"><B>Procedural History</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">Petitioners have sought, by invoking the<BR ALIGN='left'/>doctrine of Gregory v. Helvering, 1935,<BR ALIGN='left'/>293 U.S. 465, 55 S.Ct. 266, 79 L.Ed.<BR ALIGN='left'/>596, 97 A.L.R. 1355, to avoid the tax<BR ALIGN='left'/>consequences of a transaction falling<BR ALIGN='left'/>within the literal language of the<BR ALIGN='left'/>statutory definition of a<BR ALIGN='left'/>&quot;reorganization&quot;. I.R.C. § 112(g) (1)<BR ALIGN='left'/>(D), 26 U.S.C.A. § 112(g) (1) (D). On<BR ALIGN='left'/>the first petition, we vacated the Tax<BR ALIGN='left'/>Court&#x27;s decision, reported in 1946, 6 T.<BR ALIGN='left'/>C. 455, and remanded the case for<BR ALIGN='left'/>further proceedings. 1 Cir., 1947, 160<BR ALIGN='left'/>F.2d 839.</TD></TR>
