<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="1" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="#d0bdf4" WIDTH="150"><B>Background Facts</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">On the fiduciary income tax return of<BR ALIGN='left'/>the Estate of John B. Lewis for the year<BR ALIGN='left'/>1941, petitioners reported the gain on<BR ALIGN='left'/>the exchange of the old company&#x27;s shares<BR ALIGN='left'/>as a long-term capital gain under I.R.C.<BR ALIGN='left'/>§§ 115(c) and 117, 26 U.S.C.A. §§<BR ALIGN='left'/>115(c), 117, realized upon the complete<BR ALIGN='left'/>liquidation of the old company. The<BR ALIGN='left'/>Commissioner determined a deficiency on<BR ALIGN='left'/>the grounds that the liquidating<BR ALIGN='left'/>distribution to petitioners by the old<BR ALIGN='left'/>company was made pursuant to a plan of<BR ALIGN='left'/>reorganization; that under § 112(c) (1)<BR ALIGN='left'/>the gain was recognized in full since it<BR ALIGN='left'/>was less than the value of the &quot;boot&quot;,<BR ALIGN='left'/>that is, the cash and securities (other<BR ALIGN='left'/>than the stock of the new company)<BR ALIGN='left'/>distributed; and that since the<BR ALIGN='left'/>distribution had the effect of a<BR ALIGN='left'/>dividend, it was taxable as such<BR ALIGN='left'/>pursuant to § 112(c) (2). On the basis<BR ALIGN='left'/>of the above findings, the Tax Court<BR ALIGN='left'/>sustained the Commissioner. This<BR ALIGN='left'/>decision of the Tax Court is now before<BR ALIGN='left'/>us on review.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
>]
